{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506490"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:43:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2540"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:12:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:12:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2540"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2540"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.17,0.43,0.26,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102185"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2540"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2540"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43180"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102185"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic and is diagnosed with essential hypertension. He has a medical history of hypercholesterolaemia. His only regular medication is rosuvastatin. He is a lifetime non-smoker and drinks one to two alcoholic drinks per week. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis General Practitioner decides to start him on perindopril 5 mg once daily and order some blood tests. Two weeks later, blood tests reveal that his creatinine has increased from 120 \u00b5mol/L to 150 \u00b5mol/L (50-120).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cease perindopril","Reduce perindopril dose to 2.5 mg","Continue current dose and check serum creatinine in one month","Switch to angiotensin II receptor blocker","Take perindopril on alternate days"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has experienced an increase in serum creatinine following the initiation of an ACE inhibitor (perindopril). It\u0027s common for serum creatinine to rise after starting ACE inhibitors due to their effect on renal hemodynamics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current dose and check serum creatinine in one month\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management in this case. An initial increase in creatinine of less than 30% from baseline is generally considered acceptable when starting an ACE inhibitor. In this patient, the increase is exactly 25% (from 120 to 150 \u00b5mol/L), which falls within the acceptable range. The current dose can be continued, but it\u0027s important to monitor renal function to ensure it stabilises, which typically occurs within two months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the creatinine had risen more than 30% from baseline. In this case, the rise is within acceptable limits, so cessation is not necessary. If renal function declines by more than 30% after starting an ACE inhibitor, bilateral renal artery stenosis should be considered as a possible cause. In this condition, glomerular filtration pressure is maintained by angiotensin II-mediated efferent arteriolar constriction; blocking this mechanism with an ACE inhibitor can significantly reduce filtration pressure, leading to acute kidney injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing perindopril dose to 2.5 mg\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this point. Dose reduction would be considered if the creatinine rise was more significant or if the patient had pre-existing renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to angiotensin II receptor blocker\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. ARBs have similar effects on renal function as ACE inhibitors, and the same monitoring principles apply. There\u0027s no advantage to switching in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETaking perindopril on alternate days\u003C/strong\u003E is a strategy sometimes used in patients with known renal impairment, but it\u0027s not necessary in this case where the creatinine rise is within acceptable limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while a creatinine increase of less than 30% is acceptable, ongoing monitoring is crucial. The patient\u0027s renal function should be checked again in about a month to ensure it has stabilised. If it continues to rise or exceeds the 30% threshold, then dose reduction or cessation of the ACE inhibitor would need to be considered. Additionally, other factors that could contribute to acute kidney injury, such as volume depletion or use of nephrotoxic medications, should be assessed and addressed if present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A serum creatinine increase \u003C 30% is acceptable following commencement of an ACE inhibitor.","Regular monitoring of renal function is essential after starting ACE inhibitors, especially in the first two months."],"references":["Australian Medicines Handbook. Adelaide. 2021. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/auth","Ahmed A. Use of angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors in patients with heart failure and renal insufficiency: how concerned should we be by the rise in serum creatinine? J Am Geriatr Soc. 2002 Jul;50(7):1297-300. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12133029/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2540"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-10T09:29:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-10T09:30:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2540"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102185"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"head